questionTemplates.text:
M: Shall we see a film this evening?
W: Oh, sorry. I'm afraid I can't. I'm seeing my Mum off at the airport at 7:30.
{a}

M: Can you believe I just had to pay 20 pounds for a hair cut in Steward?
W: You should try the salon where I go. It's only 10. But it takes a while to get an appointment.
{a}

M: What is Mr. Peterson going to do with his old house on London Road? Rent it or sell it?
W: I heard he is thinking of turning it into a restaurant, which isn't a bad idea, because it's still a solid building.
{a}

M: Good morning, Madam. What can I do for you?
W: Good morning. How much should I pay for these books to be sent to New York?
{a}

W: From here, the mountains look as if you could just reach out and touch them.
M: That's why I chose this lodge. It has one of the best views in Switzerland.
{a}

M: We could go to a ball game this evening or would you rather eat in a restaurant and then see a film?
W: To tell you the truth, I can't really go anywhere this evening, because I'm expecting an important phone call.
{a}

M: What's the trouble, Mary?
W: Well, doctor. It's my eyes. I can't see clearly.
{a}

W: Tony's mother has invited me to dinner. Do you think I should tell her in advance that I'm a vegetarian?
M: Of course. I think she'd appreciate it. Imaging how you both feel if she fixed the turkey dinner or something.
{a}

W: Why are you visiting Hong Kong?
M: I'm just on holiday.
{a}

W: I'm busy year after year,but I've done nothing.
M: You've done a lot, my darling!
{a}

W: I'm glad I don't have your job, working all night and sleeping in the daytime.
M: Oh. I stooped that when I got my promotion. Now I'm on three days and off two days.
{a}

M: I like light music. What about you, Tina?
W: Pop music.
{a}

W: Can you tell me your dream?
M: I dream of becoming a lawyer in the future.
{a}

W: Did you start the quarrel with Mary?
M: Yes, she broke my glass and didn't say sorry to me.
{a}

W: The concert starts at eight thirty. What time is it now?
M: About ten to eight. We must hurry up.
{a}

W: Your house is bigger than mine.
M: So is Bib's but Tom's is smaller.
{a}

M: I'd like to buy that coat. But I don't have enough money.
W: Would you like me to lend you some? But I'm not sure about the style.
{a}

W: Tom, was it three months ago that you luckily got an opportunity to spend your holiday in Sydney?
M: Not me. John was the lucky dog.
{a}

W: Do you get up at 5 every morning?
M: Yes, and I need 7 hours of sleep, I should go to bed by 9 or 10.
{a}

M: That was a long jog! I'm all out of breath, and you look like you are not even tired.
W: Well, I've been doing this every morning for the last ten years, you know...
{a}

M: I hear the guy who is going to deliver the lecture this weekend spend a year living in the rainforest.
W: Great. I'm doing a report on the rainforest. Maybe I can get some new information to add to it.
{a}

M: It's been raining since Monday, but the weather report says that tomorrow will be clear and sunny. Thank goodness, we can at last say goodbye to the rain.
W: That's really good news. You know I always play football on Saturday, and I like to play in good weather.
{a}

M: Hurry up. We'll be late for the concert.
W: It's only 7 o'clock now. It only takes 5 minutes to get there. There will be plenty of time if we leave at 7:15.
{a}

M: The doctor said if I kept smoking, I would increase my chances of having a heart attack.
W: Did he suggest reducing weight, too?
{a}
